<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-329-145  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 329 145.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Systems News  Feb 13 1989 n404 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Europe expands chip tariff policy.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Peterson, Stacey.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>More semiconductor chips imported to Europe are subject to importduties as a result of a European Community (EC) ruling statingthat chips must now be diffused within the EC to qualify asEC-made and not subject to a 14-percent import tariff.andP;  Formerly,chips were counted as EC-made if they were diffused elsewhere butassembled and tested in EC countries.andP;  Diffusion is the process ofetching circuitry into silicon.andP;  The cost of chips is on average40 percent of the total cost of a computer system.andP;  It is unlikelythat EC production can supply customer needs in the immediatefuture.andP;  EC companies supplied about 17 percent of the region'sdynamic memory chips and 38 percent of all local semiconductorsused in 1988, according to market research.andP;  US trade officialshave not decided whether to dispute the rule.andP;  Trade associationactivities and international negotiations could eliminate thetariff in several years.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     TariffIntegrated CircuitsEuropean Economic CommunityDiffusionMemoryInternational TradeImportEurope.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>